ed","1425–1509":"1425–1509","1359–1417":"1359–1417","1359–1442":"1359–1442","1425":"1425","1359":"1359","1401":"1401","1455":"1455","1442":"1442","1509":"1509","1417":"1417","Hardwick, Bedfordshire, England":"Hardwick, Bedfordshire, England","England":"England","Derby, Derbyshire, England":"Derby, Derbyshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Snelling","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","from the Middle English personal name <i>Snelling</i> (Old English <i>Snelling</i>), a derivative of   Snell  .","habitational name from Snelland (Lincolnshire), from the Old English personal name <i>Snell</i> (genitive <i>Snelles</i>) or the Old Norse personal name <i>Snjallr</i> (genitive <i>Snjalls</i>) + Old Norse <i>lúndr</i> ‘small wood, grove’. See   Snell  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Snell","meanings":["English: nickname for a quick, lively, or courageous person, from Middle English <i>snel(l)</i> ‘swift, vivacious, brisk, bold’ (Old English <i>snel(l)</i>, Old Norse <i>snjallr</i>). See also   Sneller  ,   Snelling  .","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Snel(l)</i> (Old English <i>Snell</i>, Old Norse <i>Snjallr</i>, with the same origins as the nickname above).","Americanized form of German   Schnell   ‘quick’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":54,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John William Snelling was born in 1401, in Derby, Derbyshire, England, his father, John Mathew Snelling, was 42 and his mother, Alice May, was 43. He had at least 1 son with Elizabeth Snelling. He died in 1455, in his hometown, at the age of 54, and was buried in Derby, Derbyshire, England."},"et":{"1401–1455":"1401–1455","1401–Female":"1401–Surnud","1425–1509":"1425–1509","1359–1417":"1359–1417","1359–1442":"1359–1442","1425":"1425","1359":"1359","1401":"1401","1455":"1455","1442":"1442","1509":"1509","1417":"1417","Hardwick, Bedfordshire, England":"Hardwick, Bedfordshire, England","England":"England","Derby, Derbyshire, England":"Derby, Derbyshire, England"},"fi":{"1401–1455":"1401–1455","1401–Female":"1401–Kuollut","1425–1509":"1425–1509","1359–1417":"1359–1417","1359–1442":"1359–1442","1425":"1425","1359":"1359","1401":"1401","1455":"1455","1442":"1442","1509":"1509","1417":"1417","Hardwick, Bedfordshire, England":"Hardwick, Bedf